The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, March 09, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 8: The National Pharmaceutical Pricing Authority has revised the prices of several bulk drugs which includes double digit percentage decrease in the case of Vitamin C and A. The prices of Vitamin C (plain) has gone down by 10.23 per cent from Rs 557 to Rs 500 per kg. For Vitamin C, the price decrease has been 10.43 per cent from Rs 556 to Rs 498 per kg. The prices of bulk drugs and derivatives have gone down due to reduction in the customs duty and abolition of the Special Additional Duty, a government release said. The exercise has been carried out in order to pass on the benefit of reduction of duties to the consumers. 																								 Mumbai, March 8: Associated Cement Companies Ltd (ACC) would issue foreign currency convertible bonds and global depository receipts to certain overseas investors, the company informed the Bombay Stock Exchange today.																								 Mumbai, March 8: Hindustan Petroleum Corporation Ltd (HPCL) today signed a non-binding MoU with Shell India Pvt Ltd covering inter alia development of product supply and infrastructure sharing agreement.																								 Mumbai, March 8: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has suspended registration certificates of two Calcutta Stock Exchange members, Mehta amp; Ajmera and Himangshu Ajmera, for one year for their failure to co-operate with Sebis inspection of synchronised transactions in DSQ Softwares scrip.																								 New Delhi, March 8: Morepen Labs said it has received a fresh approval from US Food and Drug Administration for its active pharmaceutical ingredient manufacturing facilities at Masulkhana in Himachal Pradesh.																								 New Delhi, March 8: Mahindra and Mahindra (M amp;M) today said it has begun preliminary talks to buy the engine and transmission units of Daewoo Motors India.																								 Mumbai, March 8: The Netherlands-based ABN Amro Bank has identified India as one of the six key markets for its working capital services.
